entry.title: Check if profile exists before starting DownloadActivity
entry.content:
DownloadActivity#onCreate calls OTRProfileID#deserialize to get the

OTRProfileID from intent. In some cases this causes a crashes due to

the OTR profile not being available for a given OTRProfileID. This was

previously fixed by adding a check in

DownloadUtils#showDownloadManager() before starting DownloadActivity.

However, the DownloadActivity#onCreate can still be called without

going through the check in DownloadUtils#showDownloadManager(), for

example: when the activity is killed in the background and needs to be

restarted.

This change adds an additional check to DownloadActivity before calling

OTRProfileID#deserialize.

entry.title: [Autofill] Reorganise ContentAutofillDriver, AutofillDriverRouter
entry.content:
The members of ContentAutofillDriver and AutofillDriverRouter fall

into a few groups, the two largest of which consist of events that

are routed between drivers, with one group consisting of

browser->renderer events and the other vice versa.



Maintaining this has proved difficult: some newly added functions

ended up in the wrong group, leading to incorrect comments.



This CL updates the organisation of the files and updates several

comments. It splits the two main groups into subgroups depending

on how they are routed:

- broadcast to all drivers or managers;

- routed to a specific agent or manager;

- passed on to the driver's agent.



This CL also extends comments in autofill_driver_router.cc to

explain why some events are broadcast.



Finally, this CL renames TriggerFormExtraction() to

TriggerFormExtractionInDriverFrame() to make the contrast to

TriggerFormExtractionInAllFrames() more explicit.

entry.title: LoAF: change the way script nesting is handled
entry.content:
The logic to avoid nested scripts (only count for entry points)

was not handling the fact that script blocks can be nested in

callbacks and vice-versa.



The stack is a lot clearer now, with all script probes calling

PushScriptEntryPoint & PopScriptEntryPoint, the exception being

promise-resolver, which pops only when the task is complete.



The probe handling for script blocks is now changed, so that

ExecuteScript either creates a module entry or sets the execution time

on a script that has started.



Moved script internal timings (layout/style/alert/sync-XHR) to the end of the file (unmodified).



Added a few tests that reproduce the nesting issue, and removed the test

that relies on trusted-types as we don't require that dependency.



Also this fix changes a few existing test results:

- A script block executed synchronously from within a callback is

attributed to the callback, as it's nested. The way to reproduce

a top level classic script block is to have it parsed from the

HTML.



- There is no more "execute-script" type, that's now a module.

entry.content:
AddAccount from the web is triggered when the web page is done loading.

available to display the AddAccount from the web.

enough. If the AddAccount is triggered while a view controller is

in progress to appear on the screen, this test returns NO.

entry.title: [//ash] Add MappableSI flow in ViewTreeHostRootViewFrameFactory
entry.content:
This CL adds a flow wherein ViewTreeHostRootViewFrameFactory uses

MappableSharedImage rather than GpuMemoryBuffer to create and map the

underlying buffer that it is using. The new flow is disabled by default;

a followup CL will change it to be enabled by default so that in the

case of any problems just *that* CL can be reverted.



The change is technically straightforward. However, determining its

correctness requires two key points of analysis:



* ViewTreeHostUiResource calls DestroySharedImage() on its SI in its

destructor, which is also when it destroys the GpuMemoryBuffer that

it is holding in an std::unique_ptr. Hence, the lifetimes match up.

* The UiResources that this class creates and puts into the

UiResourceManager are used *only* by this class, and hence we don't

have to worry about any other clients using these resources that now

don't have GpuMemoryBuffers in them. The reasoning behind that is that

the way to reuse a resource that has been put into the

UiResourceManager is to call

UiResourceManager::FindResourceToReuse(). That function has only three

callers, each of which occur only (transitively) from

CreateCompositorFrame() in three concrete subclasses of FrameSinkHost:

ViewTreeHostRootView (which calls the one being invoked by

ViewTreeHostRootViewFrameFactory here), FaskInkHost, and

RoundedDisplayHost. The UiResourceManager passed into the

FrameSinkHost::CreateCompositorFrame() function is owned by

the FrameSinkHost instance in question (via its FrameSinkHolder ivar).

Hence, the UiResources used by ViewTreeHostRootViewFrameFactory cannot

"escape" to the other callers of

UiResourceManager::FindResourceToReuse(), as they occur on distinct

UiResourceManager instances.



Bug: 1431263

entry.title: Sync: Make SESSIONS the canonical (and only) type for kTabs
entry.content:
Before this CL, UserSelectableType::kTabs included PROXY_TABS as the

canonical type, plus SESSIONS. This CL removes PROXY_TABS and makes

SESSIONS the canonical type.



This will affect some histograms that record the canonical type,

notably Sync.CustomSync3, but should otherwise have no effect.



Background:

PROXY_TABS was a "proxy" (i.e. fake) data type, which was used as a

"flag" to indicate whether "Open Tabs" sync was enabled. This was

necessary back when the SESSIONS data type was used for both "Open

Tabs" and "History". That's no longer the case, so PROXY_TABS isn't

needed anymore.

This CL is one more step towards fully removing it.

entry.title: Cellular: Changes to prepare suppress text messages enabled by default
entry.content:
As we plan to launch the client side in M120, the suppress text

messages feature is going to be enabled. While testing locally with

the flag enabled by default we found some test failures. This

CL fixes those failures.



1. Having a raw_ptr to NetworkMetadataStore causes dangling ptrs in

some tests, the fix for this is to just make the raw_ptr a weak_ptr

following dangling ptr check document.



2. Error logs on startup due to GUID resolution, this was fixed

by moving the GUID computation on message receipt rather than on

creating the device. This also helps us in cases when the GUID

actually changes in session (as that can happen after connecting to

an eSIM for the first time in the session)

entry.title: [Promise Icons] Remove TWA promise apps created by Play Store
entry.content:
Currently, TWA promise apps created by the Play Store do not get

deleted at the end of the installation. This is because TWA promise

apps (which listen to ARC installation events) have a package ID in

the ARC app format to reflect their installation source. However, when

the TWA finishes installing, it gets registered in the

AppRegistryCache as a web app, which would generate a web app package

ID that does not match the promise app.



To successfully remove a TWA promise app, we need to generate an ARC

package ID for installed TWAs. This requires us to check whether a web

app is a TWA and has an associated package name in the

ApkWebAppService. Since web apps installed from APKs are registered in

App Service before they are recorded in prefs (which stores the list

of all installed web app APKs), we need to expand this check to

include finding a match with any currently installing web app APKs in

the ApkWebAppService.

entry.title: Explicitly ensure unique FragmentData ID when needed.
entry.content:
Don't create a unique ID automatically as soon as FragmentData::RareData

is created. Instead make sure that one is set when we actually need it.

It's needed when setting a PaintLayer, or when setting paint properties.



The unique ID was documented as not being fragment specific, but this

turns out to be incorrect, so move it out of the non-fragment specfic

section. PaintPropertyTreeBuilder actually does set a unique ID per

fragment, and changing that to only setting it for the first fragment

would upset PropertyTreeManager::BuildEffectNodesRecursively().



No behavior changes intended.
